# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-welfare-party
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] An election for the National Assembly for Wales was held on Thursday 3 May 2007 to elect members to the National Assembly for Wales.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] On the same day local elections in England and Scotland, as well as the Scottish Parliament election took place.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] This election was preceded by the previous Assembly election in 2003.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The election saw Plaid Cymru make gains at the expense of Labour, although Labour remain the largest party in the Assembly, as they have since it began.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Plaid stated they would make a referendum on devolving further powers to the National Assembly a condition for a coalition.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Wales reported that senior civil servants before the election were preparing for three possible coalition administrations: Labour/Liberal Democrat, Labour/Plaid Cymru or Plaid Cymru/Liberal Democrat/Conservative.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Discussions between Plaid Cymru, the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats to form a "Rainbow" Coalition broke down, and a coalition was eventually agreed upon between Labour and Plaid Cymru.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The Welsh Labour Party before the election had 29 seats, Plaid Cymru had 12, the Welsh Conservatives 11, the Welsh Liberal Democrats 6, Forward Wales 1, with 1 independent, Trish Law.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Law had won her seat at a 2006 by-election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The one Forward Wales Assembly Member was elected as an independent before forming the party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The standings were otherwise identical to the 2003 results.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] In general elections for the National Assembly for Wales, each voter has two votes in a mixed member system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The first vote may be used to vote for a candidate to become the Assembly Member for the voter's constituency, elected by the first past the post system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The second vote may be used to vote for a regional closed party list of candidates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Additional member seats are allocated from the lists by the d'Hondt method, with constituency results being taken into account in the allocation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The overall result is approximately proportional.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] In South Wales West, there were also party lists from the Communist Party of Britain, Christian Peoples Alliance, Respect Party, Socialist Labour Party, Welsh Christian Party in addition to two independents, Keith James and John Hudson Jenkins.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Thirteen of the members elected to the Assembly in the election were not members of the previous Assembly, including Gareth Jones, who sat in the Assembly from 1999 to 2003 and lost his seat in that year's election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Nine sitting AMs were defeated at the polls.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Four sitting AMs did not offer themselves for re-election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] Due to boundary changes, the composition of the outgoing Assembly did not reflect the Assembly that was elected in May 2003 (see National Assembly for Wales constituencies and electoral regions).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2007-national-assembly-for-wales-election] The main changes were in northwestern Wales, where the constituencies of Conwy, Caernarfon, and Meirionydd nant Conwy were replaced by Aberconwy, Arfon and Dwyfor Meirionnydd.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The Assembly is elected by the Additional Member System.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] Fourteen directly elected constituencies exist, all of which, until 2024 were ever won by the Conservative Party or the Labour Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] An additional eleven members are allocated by a London wide top-up vote with the proviso that parties must win at least five percent of the vote to qualify for the list seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] Prior to these elections, these seats were held by five Liberal Democrats, two Labour Party members, two Green Party members and two One Londoners.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The two One London members were elected as candidates for the UK Independence Party, but then joined or supported the breakaway Veritas party and subsequently left Veritas to form One London.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] Compared to the previous election, two separate factions of RESPECT Unity Coalition stood in 2008: Respect (George Galloway), who supported Ken Livingstone in the mayoral election, and Left List, who supported Lindsey German (RESPECT's mayoral candidate in 2004).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] Labour gained Brent and Harrow from Conservative (which had been the only constituency seat changing hands in 2004, having then been gained from Labour).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The other 13 constituencies remained unchanged, with the two Liberal Democrat challenges, in South West against the Conservatives, and Lambeth and Southwark against Labour, both showing swings against the Liberal Democrats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The Labour-Conservative marginal, with just 1.3% majority, of Enfield and Haringey was defended by Labour with only a tiny swing to the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] Thus the Labour campaign for the London Assembly was considerably more successful than their campaign in the local elections held on the same day.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The Liberal Democrat and UKIP vote shares were both very poor compared with 2004, with UKIP wiped out entirely, and the Liberal Democrats losing two members.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The Labour vote share was up, but because of their capture of a FPTP seat, they did not gain any extra Additional Members against 2004.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The biggest vote increase was for the Conservatives, achieving the highest ever showing of any party on the list, 34%; as a result and also due to their loss of one FPTP seat, they went from zero to three additional members.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The Conservative record was subsequently surpassed by Labour in 2012 (41.1%) and 2016 (40.3%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] The British National Party won their first seat on the Assembly by reaching the 5% threshold.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2008-london-assembly-election] [†] Both UKIP Assembly members had subsequently defected and formed the new One London party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The **2009 European Parliament election** was the United Kingdom's component of the 2009 European Parliament election, the voting for which was held on Thursday 4 June 2009.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The election was held concurrently with the 2009 local elections in England.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] 72 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) were elected from the United Kingdom using proportional representation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The election was won by the Conservative Party, who won 27 seats with a share of 27.9% of the national vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] This was the last European election in the United Kingdom at which either the Conservatives or the Labour Party finished in first place.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Other notable outcomes were that Labour – which came third – suffered a significant drop in support, and that the UK Independence Party (UKIP) finished second in a major election for the first time in its history, coming level with Labour in terms of seats but ahead of it in terms of votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] This was the first time in British electoral history that a party in government had been outpolled in a national election by a party with no representation in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The British National Party (BNP) also won two seats, its first ever in a nationwide election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It also marked the first time the Scottish National Party (SNP) won the largest share of the European election vote in Scotland, and the first time Labour had failed to come first in a Welsh election since 1918.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was the Democratic Unionist Party (DUP)'s worst ever European election result, and also the first time an Irish Republican party, Sinn Féin, topped the polls in Northern Ireland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The United Kingdom elected 72 members of the European Parliament using proportional representation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was divided into twelve multi-member constituencies, or regions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The eleven of these regions which form Great Britain used a closed-list party list system method of proportional representation, calculated using the D'Hondt method.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Northern Ireland used the single transferable vote (STV).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The experimental use of all-postal ballots in four regions in 2004 was not repeated, resulting in a sharp reduction in turnout in those regions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] As had been the case since 1999, the electoral constituencies were based on the government's nine English regions, Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales, creating a total of 12 constituencies.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Treaty of Nice fixed the number of MEPs for the whole European Parliament at 736; as a consequence of the accession of Romania and Bulgaria in 2007, the number of seats allocated to the United Kingdom was reduced from 78 to 72.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] If the Treaty of Lisbon had entered into force by June 2009, this figure would have been 73.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] On 31 July 2007, in line with the required reduction in representation from the United Kingdom, the number of members elected from each region was modified by the Boundary Commission and Electoral Commission, based on the size of the electorate in each region.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The recommended changes were approved by the Parliament of the United Kingdom in 2008.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In the run up to the election, several polling organisations carried out public opinion polling in regards to voting intentions in Great Britain.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Results of such polls are displayed below.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] ComRes, ICM, Populus and YouGov are members of the British Polling Council, and abide by its disclosure rules.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] BPIX is not a member of the BPC, and does not publish detailed methodology and findings.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] ‡ As the number of seats was reduced, these are notional changes estimated by the BBC.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Joint ticket, ran in England as: The Christian Party - Christian Peoples Alliance.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Turnout in Great Britain was 34.3%, with 15,137,202 votes out of a total electorate of 44,171,778.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Most of the results of the election were announced on Sunday 7 June, after similar elections were held in the other 26 member states of the European Union.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Scotland declared its result on Monday 8 June, as counting in the Western Isles was delayed due to observance of the Sabbath.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Great Britain kept to the Europe-wide trend towards the right.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Labour Party, which was in its twelfth year of government of the United Kingdom, polled third and suffered a significant drop in support; UKIP finished second in a major election for the first time in its history, coming level with Labour in terms of seats but ahead of it in terms of votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Conservatives won in every region in Great Britain except the North East, where Labour won, and Scotland, where the SNP won.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Labour suffered most notably in Cornwall, where it came sixth behind Mebyon Kernow, and in the wider South West region and South East, where it polled fifth behind the Green Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The British National Party won two seats, its first ever in a national election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The share of the vote achieved by the English Democrats doubled.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The turnout in Scotland was the lowest in the United Kingdom at 28.8%, with 1,104,512 votes out of a total electorate of 3,872,975.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Scotland it was the first time the SNP won the largest share of the European election vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The SNP share of the vote rose by 9.4% points compared to 2004; this was the biggest positive swing for any party in any region in Great Britain.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Wales it was the first time since 1918 that Labour had failed to come first in a Welsh election, dropping 12.2%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Wales the Conservative Party topped the poll, with the nationalist Plaid Cymru coming a close third.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] UKIP took the fourth Welsh seat, the first time Wales had elected a UKIP MEP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Both the Liberal Democrats and the Green Party polled their lowest regional shares in Wales, though Wales was the only region where the Liberal Democrat share of the vote rose compared with 2004.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] †Seat change has been adjusted to allow for direct comparison with the results from the 2004 election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Gibraltar is a British overseas territory (BOT) and therefore is under the jurisdiction and sovereignty of the United Kingdom but does not form part of it.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Gibraltar was, however, part of the EU, the only BOT to be so, and participated as part of the South West England constituency.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Turnout was 35% in Gibraltar, below the 39% for the South West England electoral region as a whole and significantly lower than the turnout in Gibraltar in 2004.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Conservatives won with 53.3% of the votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Labour narrowly retained second place achieving 19% to the Liberal Democrats' 18.2%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was the DUP's worst ever European election result: the party had previously topped the poll in every European election in Northern Ireland since the first one in 1979.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was also the first time an Irish Republican topped the poll, Bairbre de Brún of Sinn Féin coming first with 125,000 votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The share of the votes for most parties in Northern Ireland remained essentially unchanged, the main exceptions were the DUP where their share of the vote fell by 13.8%, and the TUV, a party created by former DUP MEP Jim Allister whose share of the vote rose 13.7%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The DUP's decreased vote share was largely blamed on the TUV splitting the vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Gordon Brown faced calls for him to resign as Prime Minister following Labour's defeat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] During the 2005 Conservative leadership election, David Cameron argued for withdrawal of the Conservatives from EPP-ED and for the formation of a new group.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] After the European election it was announced that the Conservatives were leaving the EPP-ED and forming a new group, the European Conservatives and Reformists.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] On 22 June 2009, the first official list of the new group's members was released.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The group held its inaugural meeting on 24 June, during which Conservative MEP Timothy Kirkhope was named interim leader.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The first election for the group leadership was also scheduled for 14 July, pitting interim leader Kirkhope against fellow Briton Geoffrey Van Orden.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Kaminski's bid for Vice-President of the European Parliament subsequently failed, and the Poles threatened to abandon the new caucus unless Kaminski was made the group leader in the parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Similarly, UKIP helped found a new European Parliament Group, Europe of Freedom and Democracy, after the other parties in UKIP's pre-election European parliamentary grouping, Independence/Democracy, had polled badly.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Of the two BNP candidates elected to the European Parliament at the 2009 election, the UK Government announced that it would provide them both with only the bare minimum level of support, denying them the ready access to officials and information that the other 70 British MEPs received.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 6 May 2010 to elect 650 MPs to the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was the first election to be held after the minimum age of candidacy was reduced from 21 to 18.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It remains the last election in the UK to produce a Prime Minister who lasted a full term.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It resulted in the Labour government losing its 66-seat majority; however, with the opposition Conservative Party ending up with only 306 elected MPs, it was also the first election since that of February 1974 to result in a hung parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives entered government (at first in partnership with the Liberal Democrats) and remained in office for 14 years until 2024.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During the campaign, the three main party leaders engaged in the first televised debates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats achieved a breakthrough in opinion polls following the first debate, in which their leader Nick Clegg was widely seen as the strongest performer.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Nonetheless, on polling day their share of the vote increased by only 1%, with a net loss of five seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was still the Liberal Democrats' largest popular vote since the party's creation in 1988; they found themselves in a pivotal role in the formation of the new government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The share of votes for parties other than Labour or the Conservatives was 35%, the largest since the 1918 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It was the most 'three-cornered' election in terms of votes since 1923, and in terms of seats since 1929.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales won its first ever seat in the House of Commons, and the Alliance Party of Northern Ireland also gained its first elected member.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The general election saw a 5.1% national swing from Labour to the Conservatives, the third-largest since 1945.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The result in one constituency, Oldham East and Saddleworth, was subsequently declared void on petition because of illegal practices during the campaign (see 2011 Oldham East and Saddleworth by-election); it was the first such instance since 1910.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A hung parliament had been largely anticipated by the opinion polls in the run-up to the election, so politicians and voters were better prepared for the constitutional process that would follow such a result than they had been in 1974.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The coalition government that was subsequently formed was the first to result directly from a UK election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The hung parliament came about in spite of the Conservatives managing a higher share of the vote than the previous Labour government had done in 2005, when it had secured a comfortable majority.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Coalition talks began immediately between the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats, and lasted for five days.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There was an attempt to put together a Labour – Liberal Democrat coalition (though 11 seats from other smaller parties would have been required).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] To facilitate this, Gordon Brown announced on the evening of Monday 10 May that he would resign as Leader of the Labour Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Just after midnight on 12 May, the Liberal Democrats approved the coalition agreement 'overwhelmingly'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A total of 149 sitting MPs stood down at the election, the highest since 1945, including many former New Labour Cabinet ministers such as former Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott, Alan Milburn, Geoff Hoon, Ruth Kelly, James Purnell and John Reid.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] One reason for the very high number of MPs standing down was the parliamentary expenses scandal a year earlier.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A record 228 new MPs were elected at the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Many of the Conservative MPs elected for the first time became ministers in government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election took place on 6 May in 649 constituencies across the United Kingdom, under the first-past-the-post system, for seats in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Voting in the Thirsk and Malton constituency was postponed for three weeks because of the death of a candidate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The governing Labour Party campaigned to secure a fourth consecutive term in office, and to restore support lost since 2001 due to the Iraq War.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party sought to gain a dominant position in British politics after losses in the 1990s, and to replace Labour as the governing party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats hoped to make gains from both sides and hoped to hold the balance of power in a hung parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since the televised debates between the three leaders, the Lib Dems' poll ratings had risen to the point where many considered the possibility of a role for the party in forming the government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Polls just before election day saw a slight swing from the Liberal Democrats back to Labour and Conservatives, with the majority of final polls falling within one point of each of the three parties' final vote shares.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Scottish National Party, encouraged by its victory in the 2007 Scottish parliament elections, set itself a target of 20 MPs and was hoping to find itself holding a balance of power, though it ultimately fell short, winning just 6 seats – the same as in 2005.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties which had achieved success at local elections and the 2009 European elections (UK Independence Party, Green Party, British National Party, etc.) looked to extend their representation to seats in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Greens successfully achieved their first-ever seat in the House of Commons – Caroline Lucas won the constituency of Brighton Pavilion, marking a historic breakthrough for the party – though other parties failed to win any seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Democratic Unionist Party looked to maintain, if not extend, its number of seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, they instead fell from 9 to 8 seats, though they maintained their position as the fourth-largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This election had an unusually high number of MPs choosing not to seek re-election, with more standing down than did so at the 1945 general election (which on account of the extraordinary wartime circumstances came ten years after the preceding election).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This has been attributed to the 2009 expenses scandal and the fact there was talk that redundancy-style payments for departing MPs might be scrapped after the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In all, 149 MPs (100 Labour, 35 Conservatives, 7 Liberal Democrats, 2 Independents, 1 Independent Conservative and 1 member each from the SNP, Plaid Cymru, the DUP, and the SDLP) decided not to contest the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Additionally, three seats were vacant at the time of the dissolution of Parliament; two due to the deaths of Labour MPs and one due to the resignation in January 2010 of a DUP member.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Pursuant to Boundary Commission for England recommendations, the number of seats in England increased by four, and numerous changes were made to the existing constituency boundaries.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Northern Ireland continued to elect 18 MPs, but minor changes were made to the eastern constituencies in accordance with the Northern Ireland Boundary Commission's recommendations.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For the first time, these changes include the splitting of an electoral ward between two constituencies.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At the time of the election Welsh constituencies had electorates on average around 14,000 smaller than their counterparts in England.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Scotland saw its most recent large-scale review completed in 2004, so its 59 constituencies remained the same as at the 2005 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For the leaders of all three major political parties, this was their first general election contest as party leader – something that had last occurred at the 1979 election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The prospect of a coalition or minority government was being considered well before polling day.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Gordon Brown made comments about the possibility of a coalition in January 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2009, it was reported that senior civil servants were to meet with the Liberal Democrats to discuss their policies, an indication of how seriously the prospect of a hung parliament was being taken.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since that election, the SNP had won the 2007 Scottish Parliament elections and gained control of the Scottish Government, and also won the largest share of the 2009 European Parliament election vote in Scotland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Wales, the Labour Party remained the largest party in the Welsh Assembly, although Plaid Cymru increased their share of the vote and formed a coalition government with Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2009 the Ulster Unionist Party and the Conservative Party announced they had formed an electoral alliance whereby the two parties would field joint candidates for future elections under the banner of "Ulster Conservatives and Unionists – New Force".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, this caused the sole UUP MP Lady Sylvia Hermon to resign from the party on 25 March 2010, leaving them with no representation at Westminster for the first time in their history.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Many constituencies were contested by other, smaller parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2009, Nigel Farage announced his intention to resign as UKIP leader to focus on becoming an MP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage was replaced in an election by party members by Lord Pearson of Rannoch, whose stated intention was for the electoral support of UKIP to force a hung parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales voted to have a position of leader for the first time; the first leadership election was won by Caroline Lucas, who successfully contested the constituency of Brighton Pavilion.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In addition, a new loose coalition, Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition (TUSC), contested a general election for the first time.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Several members of these unions ran as candidates under the TUSC banner.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, some former members of NO2EU, such as the Liberal Party and the Communist Party of Britain, chose not to participate in the TUSC campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The coalition did not run candidates against left wing Labour or Respect candidates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The UKIP candidate for Thirsk and Malton—John Boakes—died, causing the election in the constituency to be postponed until 27 May.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Philip Lardner, the Conservative candidate for North Ayrshire and Arran, was suspended from the party for comments he made about homosexuality on his website, describing it as not "normal behaviour".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A total of 2,378 postal voters in Bristol West were wrongly sent ballot papers for Bristol East by mistake.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP attempted but failed to ban the broadcast of the final party leaders' debate in Scotland, in a court action.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They had argued that "the corporation [the BBC] had breached its rules on impartiality by excluding the SNP".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The judge, Lady Smith, ruled that "the SNP's case 'lacks the requisite precision and clarity'" and added she could not "conclude the BBC had breached impartiality rules".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Additionally, broadcasting regulator Ofcom ruled that it had not "upheld complaints received from the SNP and Plaid Cymru about The First Election Debate broadcast on ITV1 on Thursday 15 April 2010".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The leader of the UK Independence Party, Lord Pearson, wrote an open letter to Somerset newspapers, asking voters to support Conservative candidates, rather than UKIP candidates in the Somerton and Frome, Taunton Deane and Wells constituencies.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This action was criticised by UKIP candidates who refused to stand down.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Labour candidate for Bristol East and former MP Kerry McCarthy revealed information about postal votes cast in the constituency on Twitter.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Avon and Somerset Police said they were "looking into a possible alleged breach of electoral law".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The former Prime Minister Tony Blair returned to the campaign trail for Labour, visiting a polyclinic in Harrow West, following a troubled Labour campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Postal voters in the marginal Vale of Glamorgan constituency had to be issued with new ballot papers after mistakenly being told they did not have to sign applications for postal votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A group of entrepreneurs warned on the dangers of a Labour-Liberal coalition in an open letter to *The Times* on 29 April.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 28 April, Gordon Brown met Gillian Duffy, a 65-year-old woman and lifelong Labour voter from Rochdale, a Labour–Liberal Democrat marginal seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Brown's remarks were inadvertently recorded by a Sky News microphone he was still wearing, and widely broadcast.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour sources later stated that Brown had misheard Duffy and thought she had asked, "where are they fucking from?" Soon after the incident, Brown talked to Jeremy Vine live on BBC Radio 2 and publicly apologised to Duffy.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] American comedian Jon Stewart commented that the clip showed the moment when Brown's "political career leaves his body".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Brown subsequently visited Duffy to apologise in person.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Upon emerging, he described himself as a "penitent sinner", while Duffy refused to speak to the press and would not shake hands with him in front of the cameras.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] She said the incident had left her feeling more sad than angry and that she would not be voting for Labour or any other party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The incident was subsequently dubbed "Bigotgate", which was later added to the Collins English Dictionary.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Despite this, Labour went on to gain the Rochdale seat from the Liberal Democrats, one of the few gains they made in the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Hornsey and Wood Green constituency 749 postal voters were sent ballot papers which asked voters to pick three candidates instead of one; Haringey Council had to send correct versions by hand.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Metropolitan Police launched an investigation in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] *The Times* reported on 2 May that the investigation had revealed some names on the register were fictitious, with a late surge in applications to be added to the electoral register (before 20 April deadline) leading to 5,000 additions without time for full checks.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In terms of the outcome of the borough's two seats, the narrower majority in any event exceeded 5,000 votes in Poplar and Limehouse, at 6,030 votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Labour candidate for North West Norfolk, Manish Sood, described Gordon Brown as Britain's worst ever prime minister.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The comments, which he repeated to a variety of news outlets, took attention away from the previous day's speech by Brown to Citizens UK, widely described as his best in the campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A Conservative Party activist in Peterborough was arrested after alleged postal voting fraud, calling into question 150 postal votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Simon Bennett resigned as the head of the British National Party's online operation then redirected its website to his own on which he attacked the party's leadership.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the morning of polling day, 6 May, the former and later leader of UKIP, Nigel Farage, standing in Buckingham against the Speaker, was injured when a light banner-towing aircraft in which he was a passenger crashed near Brackley, Northamptonshire.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Groups of voters waiting in queues at 10 pm were locked out of polling stations in Sheffield Hallam, Manchester and Leeds; and police said one London polling station was open until 10.30 pm, which triggered a national review of polling station requirements led by the Electoral Commission.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The counts for the Foyle and East Londonderry constituencies were suspended because of a security alert around 11 pm after a car was abandoned outside the counting centre, causing a bomb scare.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP insisted that as the leading political party in Scotland in the latest opinion poll, it should be included in any debate broadcast in Scotland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 22 December 2009, the UKIP leader, Lord Pearson stated that his party should also be included.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following a decision by the BBC Trust not to uphold a complaint from the SNP and Plaid Cymru over their exclusion from the planned BBC debate, the SNP announced on 25 April that they would proceed with legal action over the debate scheduled for 29 April.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party said it was not trying to stop the broadcast but it wanted an SNP politician included for balance.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP lost the case, in a judgement delivered on 28 April.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since each MP is elected separately by the first past the post voting system, it is impossible to precisely project a clear election outcome from overall UK shares of the vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Not only can individual constituencies vary markedly from overall voting trends, but individual countries and regions within the UK may have a very different electoral contest that is not properly reflected in overall share of the vote figures.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Immediately following the previous general election, Labour held a double-digit lead in opinion polls.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, over the course of 2005, this lead was eroded somewhat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] By December 2005, the Conservative party showed its first small leads in opinion polls following the controversial 90 days' detention proposals and the election of David Cameron to the leadership of the Conservative party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In early 2006, opinion polls were increasingly mixed with small leads given alternately to Labour and Conservative.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] From the May 2006 local elections, in which Labour suffered significant losses, the Conservatives took a small single-digit lead in opinion polls.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour regained the lead in June 2007 following the resignation of Tony Blair and the appointment of Gordon Brown as prime minister.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] From November 2007, the Conservatives again took the lead and, from then, extended their lead into double digits, particularly in response to the MPs' expenses scandal, although there was some evidence that the lead narrowed slightly towards the end of 2009.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] By the end of February 2010, Ipsos MORI, ICM, YouGov and ComRes polls had all found a sufficient narrowing of the Conservative lead for media speculation about a hung parliament to return.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] From 15 April 2010, following the first televised debate of the party leaders, polling data changed dramatically, with the Lib Dem vote proportion rising to 28–33%, and the Conservative vote proportion falling.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In some polls, the Liberal Democrats took the lead from the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under UNS projections, this made a hung parliament highly probable, if Lib Dem performance had persisted.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] After the second debate on 22 April the polls, on average, placed the Conservatives in the lead on 33%, the Liberal Democrats in second on 30% and Labour in third on 28%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] If these polls had reflected the election day results on a uniform swing nationwide, Labour would have had the most seats in a hung Parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At 22:00 on election day, coinciding with the closure of the polls, the results of an exit poll completed by GfK NOP and Ipsos MORI on behalf of the BBC, Sky and ITV news services was announced.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Data were gathered from individuals at 130 polling stations around the country.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The results of the poll initially suggested a hung parliament with the Conservative Party 19 seats from a controlling majority; this was later adjusted to 21 seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The distribution of seats between the Conservatives, Labour, Liberal Democrats and other parties was initially suggested to be 307, 255, 59 and 29, respectively, although the seat numbers were later changed to 303, 251, 69 and 27, respectively.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Initial reaction to the exit poll by various commentators was of surprise at the apparent poor prospects for the Liberal Democrats because it was at odds with many opinion polls undertaken in the previous weeks.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The actual results showed that the exit poll was a good predictor.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A later BBC Exit poll (05:36 BST) predicted the Conservatives on 306 (20 short of an overall majority), Labour on 262 and Liberal Democrats on 55.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] National newspapers in England traditionally endorse political parties before a general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The following table shows which parties the major papers endorsed.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Turnout nationally was 65%, a rise from the 61% turnout in the 2005 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 27 May 2010 the Conservatives won the final seat of Thirsk and Malton, thus giving them 306 seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election in that constituency had been delayed because of the death of the UKIP candidate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Two results were also challenged by defeated candidates through election petitions – Fermanagh and South Tyrone, and Oldham East and Saddleworth.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] These candidates had lost by 4 and 103 votes respectively.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The defeated Unionist 'Unity' candidate, Rodney Connor, lodged a petition against the successful Sinn Féin candidate, Michelle Gildernew, in Fermanagh and South Tyrone, alleging irregularities in the counting of the votes had affected the result.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Gildernew had won with a plurality of four votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, the court found that there were only three ballot papers which could not be accounted for, and even if they were all votes for Connor, Gildernew would have had a plurality of one.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 28 May 2010, the defeated Liberal Democrat candidate Elwyn Watkins lodged a petition against the election of Phil Woolas (Labour) in Oldham East and Saddleworth constituency.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The petition challenged leaflets issued by Woolas's campaign as having contained false statements of fact concerning Watkins' personal character, which is an illegal practice under section 106 of the Representation of the People Act 1983.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The statements attempted to link Watkins with Muslim extremists and death threats to Woolas, accused him of reneging on a promise to live in the constituency, and implied that his campaign was funded by illegal foreign political donations.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During the court case a number of emails between Woolas and his campaign team emerged.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On that day Woolas was found to have breached section 106 of the Representation of the People Act 1983 in relation to three of the four statements complained about, and the judges ruled that his election was void.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Phil Woolas applied for a judicial review into the ruling, stating that "this election petition raised fundamental issues about the freedom to question and criticise politicians" and that it "will inevitably chill political speech".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He succeeded in overturning the finding in respect of one of the three statements but the main findings of the election court judgment were upheld.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A by-election on 13 January 2011 resulted in the election of Debbie Abrahams (Labour).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At 9:41 on 7 May, the BBC confirmed a hung parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives stood at 290 seats, Labour at 247 and Liberal Democrats at 51.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] One constituency seat (Thirsk and Malton) was contested on 27 May because of the death of the UKIP candidate and was won by the Conservative Party, whilst another seat (Oldham East and Saddleworth) later had its result declared void; Labour won the resulting by-election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The result showed an overall 5.1% swing from Labour to the Conservatives, the third largest national swing achieved in a general election since 1945 and similar to the 5.3% swing achieved by the Conservative leader Margaret Thatcher in 1979.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The 97 net seat gains made by the Conservatives outdid their previous best gains total in 1950, when they gained 85.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour's loss of 91 seats was worse than their previous greatest loss of seats, when they lost 77 seats in 1970.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the 532 seats contested in England (a final seat, Thirsk and Malton, was contested on 27 May), the Conservatives won 298 seats and an absolute majority of 61 seats over all other parties combined, securing an average swing of 5.6% from Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did poorly in many Southern areas, notably in the Eastern Region where they won only two of their 14 seats from 2005: Luton North and Luton South.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did, however, gain two seats: Bethnal Green and Bow and Chesterfield.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives made 95 of their gains in England, but they also suffered three losses, all to the Liberal Democrats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For the Liberal Democrats, their eight gains were overshadowed by their 12 losses – one to Labour and 11 to the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The British National Party (BNP) would record their highest ever vote in a general election with 1.9% of the popular vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This is the highest vote for a British Far-right party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] None of Scotland's 59 seats changed hands and all were held by the same party that had won them at the 2005 election, with Labour regaining the two seats they had lost in by-elections since 2005.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There was a swing to Labour from the Conservatives of 0.8% (with Labour increasing its share of the vote by 2.5% and the Conservatives increasing by just 0.9%) The Conservatives finished with just a single MP representing a Scottish constituency.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the 40 seats contested in Wales, the Conservatives more than doubled their seats from three to eight, taking one from the Liberal Democrats and four from Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Welsh nationalist party Plaid Cymru's number of seats was reduced from three to two on the new seat boundaries, but they managed to gain one seat, Arfon, from Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did, however, regain Blaenau Gwent, which had once been Labour's safest seat in Wales until it had been taken by an Independent, Peter Law, in 2005.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Overall, Labour made a net loss of 4 seats but remained the biggest party, with 26.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were 18 seats contested in Northern Ireland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Irish nationalist parties, Sinn Féin and the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP), held their seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The unionist Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) and Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) (the latter in an electoral pact with the Conservatives), lost one seat each.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This left the nationalist parties unchanged with eight seats, the main unionist parties with eight seats (all DUP), the Alliance with one seat and an independent unionist with one seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It is the first time since the partition of Ireland that unionist parties failed to secure a majority of Northern Ireland's Westminster seats in a general election, and also the first time Sinn Féin obtained the largest share of the vote in Northern Ireland at a general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The election resulted in an increase in the number of MPs from ethnic minorities from 14 to 27, including the first black and Asian female Conservative MPs, Helen Grant and Priti Patel, and the first female Muslim MPs, Rushanara Ali, Shabana Mahmood and Yasmin Qureshi.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This means that 4.2% of MPs are from an ethnic minority – in the 2001 Census, it was reported that ethnic minorities comprised 7.9% of the population.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The number of female MPs rose to 141, an increase from 19.5% to 21.7% of all MPs, and the highest ever total; the number of female Conservative MPs rose from 18 (8.6% of all Conservatives) to 48 (15.7%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Northern Ireland a swing of more than 20% resulted in DUP First Minister Peter Robinson losing his Belfast East seat to the Alliance Party's Naomi Long, giving Alliance its first elected MP in Westminster.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sir Reg Empey, leader of the UUP/Conservative alliance (UCUNF), standing for the first time in South Antrim, lost to the DUP incumbent William McCrea.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Thus both leaders of the main Unionist parties failed to win seats while the UUP for the first time had no MPs at Westminster.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A few days after the election, Empey announced that he would resign before the party conference, triggering a leadership election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sylvia Hermon, Lady Hermon retained her seat in North Down, significantly increasing her percentage of the vote despite a slightly lower turnout and her defection from the UUP/Conservative alliance to stand as an independent.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] New SDLP leader Margaret Ritchie, succeeding Eddie McGrady MP, won against Sinn Féin's Caitriona Ruane in South Down.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] All of the Sinn Féin and SDLP incumbents held their seats, although Sinn Féin's Michelle Gildernew retained her seat in Fermanagh & South Tyrone by only four votes over the Independent Unionist Unity candidate, Rodney Connor, after three recounts.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Many of the MPs who were most prominently caught up in the scandal decided, or were ordered not to stand for re-election in 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Among them were Margaret Moran, Elliot Morley, David Chaytor, Nicholas and Ann Winterton, Derek Conway, John Gummer, Douglas Hogg, Anthony Steen, Peter Viggers, Julie Kirkbride and her husband Andrew MacKay.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Where sitting MPs did stand for re-election after their expenses claims were criticised, there were some notable losses.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former Home Secretary Jacqui Smith lost her marginal Redditch seat, which showed a large 9.2% swing to the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former Home Office minister Tony McNulty lost Harrow East to the Conservatives on an 8% swing, after repaying over £13,000 claimed on a second home, occupied by his parents, which was 8 miles away from his primary residence.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ann Keen lost Brentford and Isleworth on a 6% swing, but her husband Alan Keen retained Feltham and Heston.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The couple were criticised for claiming for a second home in central London while rarely staying in their nearby constituency home.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Shahid Malik lost his Dewsbury seat on a 5.9% swing to the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Malik had been required to repay some of his expense claims and, at the time of the election, was under investigation for other claims.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] David Heathcoat-Amory was one of only two sitting Conservatives to be defeated when he lost Wells to the Liberal Democrats by 800 votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Heathcoat-Amory was criticised for claiming manure on expenses.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Phil Hope, who repaid over £40,000 in expenses, was defeated in his Corby constituency although the swing was lower than the national average at 3.3%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Hazel Blears, who had paid more than £13,000 to cover capital gains tax which she had avoided by "flipping" the designation of her main residence, suffered a large drop in her vote in Salford and Eccles, but was still comfortably re-elected; a 'Hazel must go' candidate won only 1.8%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Conversely, Brian Jenkins lost his Tamworth seat on a large 9.5% swing despite being described as a "saint" by *The Daily Telegraph* on account of his low expenses.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ironically, his successor in the seat was Conservative Chris Pincher, whose future sexual assault scandal would bring down the premiership of Prime Minister Boris Johnson twelve years later.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Predictions of a rise in the number of successful Independents in the election as a result of the 2009 expenses scandal failed to materialise.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Broadcaster Esther Rantzen gathered a great deal of publicity for her campaign in Luton South constituency where the former MP Margaret Moran had stood down, but ended up losing her deposit in 4th place with 4.4% of the vote; the winner was Moran's successor as Labour candidate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] There was also a high-profile campaign over expenses directed against Speaker John Bercow, who had 'flipped' his designation of second home.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An imperfectly observed convention states that the major parties do not oppose the Speaker seeking re-election; Bercow faced two main opponents in Buckingham.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Independent former Member of the European Parliament John Stevens, standing on the Buckinghamshire Campaign for Democracy ticket, campaigned with a man dressed in a dolphin costume whom he called 'Flipper' and polled second with 21.4%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former leader of the UK Independence Party Nigel Farage also fought the seat but came third in the vote with 17.4%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Problems occurred with voting at 27 polling places in 16 constituencies, and affected approximately 1,200 people.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This situation was condemned by politicians of various parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Jenny Watson, chair of the Electoral Commission, the independent body that oversees the electoral process, was forced on to television to defend preparations and procedures.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Electoral Commission announced it would be carrying out a "thorough investigation".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Under the law in force at the 2010 election, voters had to have been handed their ballots by the 10 pm deadline; people who were waiting in queues to vote at 10 pm were not allowed to vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Some dissatisfied voters staged sit-ins to protest against what some of them had called "disenfranchisement".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Liverpool, higher-than-expected turnout meant several polling stations ran out of ballot papers, with defeated council leader Warren Bradley stating that some residents were unable to cast their votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Wyre and Preston North, a 14-year-old boy cast a vote after being sent a polling card.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In parts of Liberal Democrat leader Nick Clegg's Sheffield Hallam seat it was reported that students from the city's two universities were placed in separate queues from 'local' residents, who were given priority, resulting in many students being unable to cast their votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] When it became clear that no party would achieve an overall majority, the three main party leaders made public statements offering to discuss the options for forming the next government with the other parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Prior to the election, Nick Clegg and Menzies Campbell had continued the position of Charles Kennedy of not being prepared to form a coalition with either main party and of voting against any Queen's Speech unless there was an unambiguous commitment in it to introduce proportional representation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] However, following the election results, Clegg shifted this position, arguing that the UK faced a 'fluid political situation' in the context of the first hung parliament in 36 years, and an urgent need for economic recovery following the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] He maintained that political leaders had a responsibility to act in the 'national interest' to provide a strong and stable government rather than pursuing narrow party gains.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Negotiations with the Labour Party were attempted but failed.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Clegg concluded that a stable coalition with Labour was impossible due to internal Labour Party revolts and the fact that even a combined Lib Dem – Labour bloc would still require the support of several smaller parties to reach a majority.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In addition, prior to the election, Clegg had stated that the party with the most votes and seats should have the 'first right' to seek to form a government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Since the Conservative Party won the most seats (306) and the highest share of the popular vote, Clegg felt a 'democratic' obligation to negotiate with them first.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Whilst the Conservatives refused to grant full proportional representation, they offered a referendum on the Alternative Vote (AV) system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Clegg accepted this as a compromise that would at least 'repair the political system' and provide a stepping stone toward broader reform.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On Wednesday 12 May, the two coalition parties jointly published the Conservative – Liberal Democrat coalition agreement.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UK parties spent £31.1m on the campaign of which Conservatives spent 53%, the Labour Party spent 25% and the Liberal Democrats 15%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Figures from returning officers show that the average administration cost per constituency was £173,846 meaning the average cost per vote was £3.81.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The **2014 European Parliament election** was the United Kingdom's component of the 2014 European Parliament election, held on Thursday 22 May 2014, coinciding with the 2014 local elections in England and Northern Ireland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In total, 73 Members of the European Parliament were elected from the United Kingdom using proportional representation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] England, Scotland and Wales use a closed-list party list system of PR (with the D'Hondt method), while Northern Ireland used the single transferable vote (STV).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Most of the election results were announced after 10pm on Sunday 25 May – with the exception of Scotland, which did not declare its results until the following day – after voting closed throughout the 28 member states of the European Union.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The most successful party overall was the UK Independence Party (UKIP) which won 24 seats and 27% of the popular vote, the first time a political party other than the Labour Party or Conservative Party had won the popular vote at a British election since the 1906 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was also the first time a party other than Labour or Conservative had won the largest number of seats in a national election since the December 1910 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In addition, the 23.1% of the vote won by the Conservatives was the lowest recorded vote share for the party in a national election until 2019.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Labour Party became the first Official Opposition party since 1984 to fail to win a European Parliament election, although it did gain 7 seats, taking its overall tally to 20.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The governing Conservative Party was pushed into third place for the first time at any European Parliament election, falling to 19 seats, while the Green Party of England and Wales saw its number of MEPs increase for the first time since 1999, winning 3 seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Scotland, the Scottish National Party won the largest share of the vote, taking 29% of the vote and 2 MEPs.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Liberal Democrats, who were in government in the UK with the Conservatives at the time, lost 10 of the 11 seats they were defending, and won just 7% of the popular vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Figures released in December 2014 showed that the Conservatives and UKIP each spent £2.96m on the campaign, the Liberal Democrats £1.5m, and the Labour Party approximately £1m.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The United Kingdom elected 73 Members of the European Parliament using proportional representation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The United Kingdom was divided into twelve multi-member constituencies.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] As a result of the Treaty of Lisbon coming into force, the UK became entitled to a 73rd MEP as from November 2011.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] 1 Includes Gibraltar, the only British Overseas Territory which was part of the European Union.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Between the 2009 and 2014 elections, there were various changes to the breakdown of UK members.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In December 2011, a 73rd member from the UK (Anthea McIntyre, Conservative) was allocated to England because of the implementation of the Treaty of Lisbon.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Ulster Conservatives and Unionists – New Force (UCUNF) electoral pact between the Conservatives and the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) was dissolved.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] 39 parties stood a total of 747 candidates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Conservative Party and UKIP had candidates in every region, as did the three Green parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the BNP had a full slate of candidates in all the regions in Great Britain (i.e. excluding Northern Ireland).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The English Democrats and An Independence from Europe had a full slate of candidates in all the English regions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] No2EU had a full slate in seven regions, while Britain First and the Socialist Party of Great Britain had full slates in two regions each.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Harmony Party stood in four regions and the Christian Peoples Alliance in three regions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] On 20 February, the Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg used his weekly phone-in show on LBC 97.3 to challenge the leader of the UK Independence Party, Nigel Farage, to a live public debate on the UK's membership of the European Union.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Clegg said, "he is the leader of the party of 'out'; I am the leader of the party of 'in'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] I think it's time we now have a proper, public debate so that the public can listen to the two sides of the argument and judge from themselves." Farage accepted, but said he would also like to see Ed Miliband and David Cameron participate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The first hour-long debate between the two men was held on 26 March 2014 and was broadcast live on television by Sky News and on the BBC News Channel.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The debate was hosted by LBC and moderated by Nick Ferrari.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] After the first debate, a YouGov poll asked "Who performed better?", with 57% saying Farage did better compared to 36% for Clegg.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The second debate was held on BBC Two on 2 April in a special programme called *The European Union: In or Out*, moderated by David Dimbleby.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Farage was again seen as outperforming his rival, with a snap poll by YouGov showing 68% of people thought he did better in the debate compared to 27% for Clegg.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] A snap *Guardian* poll also showed that 69% thought Farage won the debate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Despite David Cameron and Ed Miliband declining to participate in the leaders' debates, the Conservative and Labour parties were represented in a lower-profile debate on the BBC.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] On 13 February Andrew Neil hosted a four-way debate on the BBC's *Sunday Politics* programme.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Conservatives were represented by Syed Kamall MEP, Labour by Richard Howitt MEP, the Liberal Democrats by Baroness Sarah Ludford MEP and the UK Independence Party by Patrick O'Flynn, the party's Director of communications and an MEP candidate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] These opinion polls are for Great Britain and generally exclude Northern Ireland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The methodology used for these polls broadly corresponds to that used for opinion polling for the 2015 United Kingdom general election; see that article for the methodology used by each polling company.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Data for these polls are generally gathered at the same time as the data for General Election polling.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The UK Independence Party (UKIP) came top of the poll, the first time a political party other than the Labour Party or Conservative Party had won the popular vote at a British election since the 1906 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] However, by the end of 2018, following multiple departures and other changes, only 9 MEPs remained affiliated to UKIP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] By February 2019, there were only 7 UKIP MEPs, while 7 former UKIP MEPs had joined the new Brexit Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It concurrently won the largest share of the vote in 100 council areas, with its largest vote share recorded in Newham at 58.4%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The governing Conservative Party was pushed into third place for the first time at any European Parliament election, winning just 23.3% of the national vote share and losing 7 seats to fall to 19 overall, one behind Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It won the largest share of the vote in just 89 council areas and its highest vote was recorded in Elmbridge at 43.1%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Green Party of England and Wales saw its number of MEPs increase for the first time since 1999, winning a total of 3 seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The party rose from fifth place to fourth, although its vote share declined slightly compared to 2009.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] This was the first time since 1989 that the Greens had outpolled the Liberal Democrats in a European election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Scotland, the Scottish National Party won the largest share of the vote taking 28.9% of the vote and retained its two of the six Scottish seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Liberal Democrats, who were in coalition with the Conservatives at the time, lost ten of the eleven seats they were defending and won just 6.9% of the vote share nationally.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2014-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Their highest vote share was recorded in Gibraltar, where they won a 67.2% share of the vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 7 May 2015 to elect 650 members of Parliament (MPs) to the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party, led by Prime Minister David Cameron, won an unexpected majority victory of 10 seats; they had been leading a coalition government with the Liberal Democrats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It was the last general election to be held before the UK voted to leave the European Union (EU) in June 2016.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It was the first of three general elections to be held under the rules of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Local elections took place in most areas of England on the same day and is to date the most recent general election to coincide with local elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Opinion polls and political commentators had widely predicted that the election would result in a second consecutive hung parliament whose composition would be similar to the one elected at the previous general election in 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Potential coalitions and agreements between parties were intensively discussed; as a result, smaller parties received much more attention during the campaign than in previous UK elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, opinion polls underestimated the Conservatives, as they won 330 of the 650 seats and 36.9 per cent of the vote, giving them a small overall majority.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The opposition Labour Party, led by Ed Miliband, saw a small increase in vote share to 30.4 per cent, but it returned 232 MPs, 26 fewer than in 2010 and their fewest since the 1987 general election, when it had 229 MPs.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour lost significant ground in Scotland to the Scottish National Party (SNP) who enjoyed a huge surge, winning 56 of the 59 Scottish seats, becoming the third-largest party in the House of Commons and the largest party in Scotland, knocking Labour from the status which it had held since 1964.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats, junior coalition partners led by Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg, suffered heavy losses, losing 49 of their 57 seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Returning just eight MPs, it was their worst result since 1970 when its predecessors party, the Liberal Party, returned six MPs.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Cabinet ministers Vince Cable, Ed Davey, and Danny Alexander lost their seats, whilst Clegg only narrowly held his own seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The UK Independence Party (UKIP) received 12.6 per cent of the vote, displacing the Liberal Democrats as the third-placed party in terms of popular vote, but won only one seat: Clacton, which they had gained at a by-election six months earlier.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They failed to retain their other seat gained in a by-election, Rochester and Strood, and the party's leader, Nigel Farage, ran in South Thanet but did not win the seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales won its highest vote share unto that point at 3.8%, and their only MP, Caroline Lucas, retained her seat, Brighton Pavilion.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following the election, Miliband and Clegg resigned their leaderships.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Jeremy Corbyn succeeded Miliband as Leader of the Labour Party, while Tim Farron succeeded Clegg as Leader of the Liberal Democrats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP began a nine-year domination of Scottish Westminster seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Charles Kennedy, who served as the leader of the Liberal Democrats from 1999 to 2006, made his last public appearance during the election campaign, in which he lost his seat; he died on 1 June 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Notable MPs who retired at this election included former prime minister and Labour leader Gordon Brown, former Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling, former leader of the opposition and Conservative leader William Hague, and former leader of the Liberal Democrats Menzies Campbell.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Another future prime minister and Conservative leader, Boris Johnson, who had previously left Parliament in 2008 so he could serve as the mayor of London, returned to Parliament as MP for Uxbridge and South Ruislip.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 led to the dissolution of the 55th Parliament on 30 March 2015 and the scheduling of the election on 7 May.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were local elections on the same day in all of England, with the exception of Greater London.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] No elections were scheduled to take place in Scotland, Wales, or Northern Ireland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] All British, Irish, and Commonwealth citizens over the age of 18 and residing in the UK who were not in prison or a mental hospital or a fugitive on the date of the election were permitted to vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In British general elections, voting takes place in all constituencies in the United Kingdom to elect Members of Parliament to the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament in the UK.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Each constituency elects one MP using the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] If one party obtains a majority (326) of the 650 seats, then that party is entitled to form the government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] If no party has a majority, then there is what is known as a hung parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In this case, the options for forming the Government are either a minority government (where one party governs alone despite not having the majority of the seats) or a coalition government (where one party governs alongside party in order to get a majority of seats).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The next boundary review was set to take place in 2018, so the 2015 general election was contested using the same constituencies and boundaries as in 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the 650 constituencies, 533 were in England, 59 were in Scotland, 40 were in Wales and 18 were in Northern Ireland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In addition, the 2011 Act mandated a referendum in 2011 on changing from the first-past-the-post voting system to an alternative vote system for general elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government agreed to holding a referendum.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The referendum was held in May 2011 and resulted in the retention of the existing voting system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Before the previous general election the Liberal Democrats had pledged to change the voting system, and the Labour Party had pledged to hold a referendum on any such change.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives, however, promised to keep the first-past-the-post system, but to reduce the number of constituencies to 600.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Liberal Democrats' plan was to reduce the number of MPs to 500, and for them to be elected using a proportional vote system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Government increased the amount of money that parties and candidates were allowed to spend on campaigning during the election by 23%, a move decided against the advice of the Electoral Commission.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election saw the first cap on spending by parties in individual constituencies during the 100 days before Parliament's dissolution on 30 March: £30,700, plus a per-voter allowance of 9p in county constituencies and 6p in borough seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] An additional voter allowance of more than £8,700 is available after the dissolution of Parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In total, parties spent £31.1m in the 2010 general election, of which the Conservative Party spent 53%, the Labour Party spent 25% and the Liberal Democrats 15%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was also the first UK general election to use individual rather than household voter registration.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] An election is called following the dissolution of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The 2015 general election was the first to be held under the provisions of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Prior to this, the power to dissolve Parliament was a royal prerogative, exercised by the sovereign on the advice of the prime minister.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under the provisions of the Septennial Act 1715, as amended by the Parliament Act 1911, an election had to be announced on or before the fifth anniversary of the beginning of the previous parliament, barring exceptional circumstances.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Prior to the 2010 general election, Labour and the Liberal Democrats pledged to introduce fixed-term elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] As part of the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition agreement, the Cameron ministry agreed to support legislation for fixed-term Parliaments, with the date of the next general election being 7 May 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This resulted in the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, which removed the prime minister's power to advise the monarch to call an early election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Act only permits an early dissolution if Parliament votes for one by a two-thirds supermajority, or if a majority of MPs pass a vote of no confidence and no new government is subsequently formed within 14 days.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, the prime minister had the power, by order made by Statutory Instrument under section 1(5) of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, to fix the polling day to be up to two months later than 7 May 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Such a Statutory Instrument must be approved by each House of Parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under section 14 of the Electoral Registration and Administration Act 2013, the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 was amended to extend the period between the dissolution of Parliament and the following general election polling day from 17 to 25 working days.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This had the effect of moving forward the date of the dissolution of the Parliament to 30 March 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] While at the previous election there had been a record 149 MPs not standing for re-election, the 2015 election saw 89 MPs standing down.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Out of these MPs, 37 were Conservatives, 37 were Labour, 10 were Liberal Democrats, 3 were Independents, 1 was Sinn Féin and 1 was Plaid Cymru.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The highest-profile members of parliament leaving were: Gordon Brown, the former Prime Minister, and William Hague, the former Leader of the Conservative Party and Leader of the Opposition.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Alongside Brown and Hague, 17 former cabinet ministers stood down at the election, including Stephen Dorrell, Jack Straw, Alistair Darling, David Blunkett, Sir Malcolm Rifkind and Dame Tessa Jowell.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The highest-profile Liberal Democrat to stand down was their former leader Sir Menzies Campbell, while the longest-serving MP, Sir Peter Tapsell, also retired, having served as an MP continuously since 1966, or for 49 years.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 9 April 2015, the deadline for standing for the general election, there were 464 political parties registered with the Electoral Commission.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Candidates who did not belong to a party were either labelled as an Independent or not labelled at all.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party and the Labour Party had been the two biggest parties since 1922.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Every prime minister to serve since 1935 had been the leader of the Conservatives or Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats had been the third largest party in the UK for many years; but as described by various political commentators, other parties had risen relative to the Liberal Democrats since the 2010 election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The BBC's guidelines were similar but removed UKIP from their list of major parties, and instead stated that UKIP should be given "appropriate levels of coverage in output to which the largest parties contribute and, on some occasions, similar levels of coverage".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Seven parties participated in the election leadership debates: Conservative, Labour, Liberal Democrat, UKIP, SNP, PC and Green.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Northern Ireland's political parties were not included in any debates, despite the DUP, a party based in Northern Ireland, being the fourth largest party in the UK going into the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Several parties operate in specific regions only.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Dozens of minor parties stood in this election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition stood 135 candidates and was the only minor party to have more than forty candidates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Respect Party, who came into the election with one MP who was elected at the 2012 Bradford West by-election, stood four candidates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The British National Party, who finished fifth with 1.9% of the vote and stood 338 candidates at the 2010 general election, stood only eight candidates this year following a collapse in their support.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Seven hundred fifty-three other candidates stood at the general election, including Independents and candidates from other parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties in Northern Ireland included the Traditional Unionist Voice, who won no seats at this election but had one member of the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Conservatives and UKIP (both are major parties in the rest of the UK, but are minor parties here).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties in Scotland include the Scottish Libertarian Party, but none of the smaller parties make much of an impact in general elections in Scotland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Wales has a number of smaller parties which, again, do not tend to make much impact in the general elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2015, the Labour Party continued to dominate Welsh politics at the general elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Coalitions have been rare in the United Kingdom, because the system of first-past-the-post voting has usually led to one party winning an overall majority in the Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, with the outgoing Government being a coalition and with opinion polls not showing a large or consistent lead for any one party, there was much discussion about possible post-election coalitions or other arrangements, such as confidence and supply agreements.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Some UK political parties that only stand in part of the country have reciprocal relationships with parties standing in other parts of the country.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 17 March 2015 the Democratic Unionist Party and the Ulster Unionist Party agreed an election pact, whereby the DUP would not stand candidates in Fermanagh and South Tyrone (where Michelle Gildernew, the Sinn Féin candidate, won by only four votes in 2010) and in Newry and Armagh.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In return the UUP would stand aside in Belfast East and Belfast North.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SDLP rejected a similar pact suggested by Sinn Féin to try to ensure that an agreed nationalist would win that constituency.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The DUP also called on voters in Scotland to support whichever pro-Union candidate was best placed to beat the SNP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The deadline for parties and individuals to file candidate nomination papers to the acting returning officer (and the deadline for candidates to withdraw) was 4 p.m. on 9 April 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The total number of candidates was 3,971; the second-highest number in history, slightly down from the record 4,150 candidates at the last election in 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were a record number of female candidates standing in terms of both absolute numbers and percentage of candidates: 1,020 (26.1%) in 2015, up from 854 (21.1%) in 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The proportion of female candidates for major parties ranged from 41% of Alliance Party candidates to 12% of UKIP candidates.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] According to UCL's Parliamentary Candidates UK project the major parties had the following percentages of black and ethnic minority candidates: the Conservatives 11%, the Liberal Democrats 10%, Labour 9%, UKIP 6%, the Greens 4%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The average age of the candidates for the seven major parties was 45.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The youngest candidates were all aged 18: Solomon Curtis (Labour, Wealden); Niamh McCarthy (Independent, Liverpool Wavertree); Michael Burrows (UKIP, Inverclyde); Declan Lloyd (Labour, South East Cornwall); and Laura-Jane Rossington (Communist Party, Plymouth Sutton and Devonport).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The oldest candidate was Doris Osen, 84, of the Elderly Persons' Independent Party (EPIC), who contested Ilford North.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Other candidates aged over 80 included three long-serving Labour MPs standing for re-election: Sir Gerald Kaufman (aged 84; Manchester Gorton), Dennis Skinner (aged 83; Bolsover) and David Winnick (aged 81; Walsall North).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following his re-election, Kaufman became Father of the House, an honorary title he held until his death in early 2017.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Several candidates, including two each for Labour and UKIP, were suspended from their respective parties after nominations were closed.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Independent candidate Ronnie Carroll died after nominations were closed.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In late 2014, six months before the election, the Conservatives decided to target Lib Dem seats as well as defending their own seats and targeting Conservative–Labour marginals, which ultimately contributed to their victory.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2015 David Cameron launched the Conservative formal campaign in Chippenham on 30 March.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Throughout the campaign the Conservatives played on fears of a Labour–SNP coalition following the Scottish independence referendum the year before.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Labour campaign was launched on 27 March at Olympic Park in London.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Ed Miliband's EdStone was a major feature of the campaign which was covered by the media.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Deputy Leader of the Labour Party Harriet Harman embarked on a pink bus tour as part of her Woman to Woman campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative manifesto committed to "a straight in-out referendum on our membership of the European Union by the end of 2017".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did not support this, but did commit to an EU membership referendum if any further powers were transferred to the European Union.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Lib Dems also supported the Labour position, but explicitly supported the UK's continuing membership of the EU.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election was the first following the 2014 Scottish independence referendum.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] None of the three major party manifestos supported a second referendum and the Conservative manifesto stated that "the question of Scotland's place in the United Kingdom is now settled".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In the run-up to the election, David Cameron coined the phrase "Carlisle principle" for the idea that checks and balances are required to ensure that devolution to Scotland has no adverse effects on other parts of the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The phrase references a fear that Carlisle, being the English town closest to the Scottish border, could be affected economically by preferential tax rates in Scotland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The deficit, who was responsible for it and plans to deal with it were a major theme of the campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] While some smaller parties opposed austerity, the Conservatives, Labour, Liberal Democrats, UKIP and the Greens all supported some further cuts, albeit to different extents.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Conservative campaigning sought to blame the deficit on the previous Labour government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour, in return, sought to establish their fiscal responsibility.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] With the Conservatives also making several spending commitments (e.g., on the NHS), commentators talked of the two main parties' 'political crossdressing', each trying to campaign on the other's traditional territory.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was also associated with a rise in multi-party politics, with increased support for UKIP, the SNP and the Greens.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The question of what the different parties would do in the likely event of an inconclusive result dominated much of the campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties focused on the power this would bring them in negotiations; Labour and the Conservatives both insisted that they were working towards winning overall majorities, while they were also reported to be preparing for the possibility of a second election later in the year.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In practice, Labour were prepared to make a 'broad' offer to the Liberal Democrats in the event of a hung parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Most predictions saw Labour as having more potential support in parliament than the Conservatives, with several parties, notably the SNP, having committed to preventing a Conservative government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives claimed a hung parliament with Labour as the largest party would result in a 'coalition of chaos', and David Cameron tweeted that the electoral choice was one between 'stable and strong government with me, or chaos with Ed Miliband'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Due to the substantial political turmoil in Britain in the years following the 2015 election, the tweet became infamous.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Conservative campaigning sought to highlight what they described as the dangers of a minority Labour administration supported by the SNP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This proved effective at dominating the agenda of the campaign and at motivating voters to support them.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The surprise Conservative victory was 'widely put down to the success of the anti-Labour/SNP warnings', according to the BBC and other media commentators.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour, in reaction, produced ever stronger denials that they would cooperate with the SNP after the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives and Lib Dems both also rejected the idea of a coalition with the SNP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was particularly notable for Labour, to whom the SNP had previously offered support: their manifesto stated that "the SNP will never put the Tories into power.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Instead, if there is an anti-Tory majority after the election, we will offer to work with other parties to keep the Tories out".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] SNP leader Nicola Sturgeon later confirmed in the Scottish leaders' debate on STV that she was prepared to 'help make Ed Miliband prime minister'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, on 26 April, Miliband ruled out a confidence and supply arrangement with the SNP too.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Miliband's comments suggested to many that he was aiming to form a minority government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats said that they would talk first to whichever party won the most seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Labour and the Liberal Democrats ruled out coalitions with UKIP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Ruth Davidson, leader of the Scottish Conservatives, asked about a deal with UKIP in the Scottish leaders' debate, replied: 'No deals with UKIP.' She continued that her preference and the Prime Minister's preference in a hung parliament was for a minority Conservative government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] UKIP said they could have supported a minority Conservative government through a confidence and supply arrangement in return for a referendum on EU membership before Christmas 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also spoke of the DUP joining UKIP in this arrangement.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] UKIP and the DUP said they would work together in Parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The DUP welcomed the possibility of a hung parliament and the influence that this would bring them.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party's deputy leader, Nigel Dodds, said they could work with the Conservatives or Labour, but that they were 'not interested in a full-blown coalition government'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Their leader, Peter Robinson, said that the DUP would talk first to whichever party wins the most seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The DUP said they wanted, for their support, a commitment to 2% defence spending, a referendum on EU membership, and a reversal of the under-occupation penalty.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They opposed the SNP being involved in government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The UUP also indicated that they would not work with the SNP if it wanted another independence referendum in Scotland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Additionally, issues were raised about the continued existence of the BBC – as the DUP, UKIP and Conservatives had made a number of statements criticising the institution – as well as support for same-sex marriage.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Plaid Cymru, the SNP, and the Green Party of England and Wales all ruled out working with the Conservatives, and agreed to work together 'wherever possible' to counter austerity.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Each would also make it a condition of any agreement with Labour that Trident nuclear weapons were not replaced; the Green Party of England and Wales stated that 'austerity is a red line'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Plaid Cymru and the Green Party stated a preference for a confidence and supply arrangement with Labour, rather than a coalition.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The leader of the SDLP, Alasdair McDonnell, said 'we will be the left-of-centre backbone of a Labour administration' and that 'the SDLP will categorically refuse to support David Cameron and the Conservative Party'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sinn Féin reiterated their abstentionist stance.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In the event, the Conservatives did, against expectations, secure a small overall majority, rendering most of the speculation and positioning moot.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The first series of televised leaders' debates in the United Kingdom was held in the previous election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Returning major party leaders Cameron and Clegg participated, as did then-prime minister Gordon Brown, who did not seek re-election in his constituency in 2015.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following much debate and various proposals, a seven-way ITV debate with the leaders of Labour, the Conservatives, Liberal Democrats, UKIP, Greens, SNP and Plaid Cymru was held on 2 April. with a series of other debates involving some of the parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A five-way BBC debate with the Labour, UKIP, Green, SNP and Plaid Cymru leaders was held on 16 April.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The other parties criticised Cameron's absence from the debate.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Finally, a *Question Time* special was broadcast on 30 April, featuring Cameron, Miliband and Clegg.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Other party leaders – Sturgeon, Wood and Farage – were given about half an hour to answer questions from an audience in *Ask ...* programs.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] *Ask Nicola Sturgeon,* *Ask Leanne Wood* and *Ask Nigel Farage* were broadcast on BBC1 afterwards.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Various newspapers, organisations and individuals endorsed parties or individual candidates for the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Despite speculation that 2015 would be the 'social media election', traditional media, particularly broadcast media, remained more influential than new digital platforms.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A majority of the public (62%) reported that TV coverage had been most influential for informing them during the election period, especially televised debates between politicians.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Newspapers were next most influential, with the *Daily Mail* influencing people's opinions most (30%), followed by *The Guardian* (21%) and *The Times* (20%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Online, major media outlets—like BBC News, newspaper websites, and Sky News—were most influential.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Social media was regarded less influential than radio and conversations with friends and family.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During the campaign, TV news coverage was dominated by horse race journalism, focusing on the how close Labour and the Conservatives were according to the polls, and speculation on possible coalition outcomes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were concerns this 'meta-coverage' was pushing policy issues to the sideline.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Policy received less than half of election news airtime across all five main TV broadcasters (BBC, ITV, Channel 4, Channel 5 and Sky) during the first five weeks of the campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On TV, these topics made up 43% of all election news coverage; within the papers, nearly a third (31%) of all election-related articles were on the economy alone.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Less attention was given to policy areas that might have been problematic for the Conservatives, like the NHS or housing (policy topics favoured by Labour) or immigration (favoured by UKIP).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Reflecting on analysis carried out during the election campaign period, David Deacon of Loughborough University's Communication Research Centre said there was 'aggressive partisanship [in] many section of the national press' which could be seen especially in the 'Tory press'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] According to Bart Cammaerts of the Media and Communications Department at the London School of Economics, during the campaign 'almost all newspapers were extremely pro-Conservative and rabidly anti-Labour'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] 57.5% of the daily newspapers backed the Conservatives, 11.7% Labour, 4.9% UKIP, and 1.4% backed a continuation of the incumbent Conservative – Liberal Democrat coalition government; 66% of Sunday national newspapers backed the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of newspaper front-page lead stories, the Conservatives received 80 positive splashes and 26 negative; Labour received 30 positive against 69 negative.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Print media was hostile towards Labour at levels 'not seen since the 1992 general election', when Neil Kinnock was 'attacked hard and hit below the belt repeatedly'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Roy Greenslade described the newspaper coverage of Labour as 'relentless ridicule'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the leader columns in *The Sun*, 95% were anti-Labour.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP also received substantial negative press in English newspapers: of the 59 leader columns about the SNP during the election, one was positive.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The *Daily Mail* ran a headline suggesting SNP leader Nicola Sturgeon was 'the most dangerous woman in Britain' and, at other times, called her a 'glamorous power-dressing imperatrix' and said that she 'would make Hillary Clinton look human'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] While the Scottish edition of *The Sun* encouraged people north of the border to vote for the SNP, the English edition encouraged people to vote for the Conservatives in order to "stop the SNP running the country".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The negative coverage of the SNP increased towards the end of the election campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At times, the Conservatives worked closely with newspapers to co-ordinate their news coverage.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For example, *The Daily Telegraph* printed a letter purportedly sent directly to the paper from 5,000 small business owners; the letter had been organised by the Conservatives and prepared at Conservative Campaign Headquarters.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] According to researchers at Cardiff University and Loughborough University, TV news agendas focused on Conservative campaign issues partly because of editorial choices to report on news originally broken in the right-leaning press but not that broken in the left-leaning press.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Researchers also found that the most airtime was given to Conservative politicians, especially in Channel 4's and Channel 5's news coverage, where they received more than a third of speaking time.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Only ITV gave more airtime to Labour spokespeople (26.9% compared with 25.1% for the Conservatives).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Airtime given to the two main political leaders, Cameron (22.4%) and Miliband (20.9%), was more balanced than that given to their parties.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties – especially the SNP – received unprecedented levels of media coverage because of speculation about a minority or coalition government.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The five most prominent politicians were David Cameron (Con) (15% of TV and press appearances), Ed Miliband (Lab) (14.7%), Nick Clegg (Lib Dem) (6.5%), Nicola Sturgeon (SNP) (5.7%), and Nigel Farage (UKIP) (5.5%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, according to analysts from Loughborough University Communication Research Centre: 'The big winners of the media coverage were the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Other than politicians, 'business sources' were the most frequently quoted in the media.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the other hand, trade union representatives, for example, received very little coverage, with business representatives receiving seven times more coverage than unions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Former prime minister Tony Blair was also in the top ten most prominent politicians (equal 9th), warning against the possibility of the UK leaving the EU.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Throughout most of the 2010–15 Parliament, Labour held a consistent polling lead over the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour overtook the Conservatives at the end of 2010 – benefiting from a collapse in Liberal Democrat support – holding a small lead throughout 2011.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Following a brief tightening in early 2012, Labour opened up a wider lead as the Conservatives suffered a slump, partially due to rising UKIP support.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UKIP passed the Liberal Democrats – whose ratings were still stagnant – as the third-placed party at the start of 2013.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Following this, Labour's lead dipped a little as UKIP also gained support from them.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour's lead gradually declined throughout 2014, largely attributed to increases in support for the SNP and the Green Party, as the Conservatives remained relatively level.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Liberal Democrat support continued to fall, dipping into single-digits.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UKIP won the most seats at the European elections in June 2014, receiving 26.6% of the vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Though their support in the polls for Westminster never reached this level, it did rise up to over 15% through the year.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Scottish independence referendum was also held in 2014; despite the 'no' vote winning, support for the Scottish National Party rose quickly after the referendum.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Wales, where polls were less frequent, the decline in Labour's lead was smaller, while UKIP and Plaid Cymru made gains.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Early 2015 saw the gap between Labour and the Conservatives continue to tighten, and by the start of the campaign at the end of March, the two parties were in a dead heat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Polling during the campaign itself remained relatively static, with the Labour and Conservative parties both polling between 33 and 34% and neither able to establish a consistent lead.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Support for the Green Party and UKIP showed slight drops, while Liberal Democrat support slightly rose up to around 9%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Scotland, support for the SNP continued to grow with polling figures in late March reaching 54%, with the Labour vote continuing to decline accordingly, while Labour retained their (reduced) lead in Wales.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The final polls showed a mixture of small Conservative and Labour leads and ties with both between 31 and 36%, UKIP on 11–16%, the Lib Dems on 8–10%, the Greens on 4–6%, and the SNP on 4–5% of the national vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The first-past-the-post system used in UK general elections means that the number of seats won is not exactly relative to vote share.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Thus, several approaches were used to convert polling data and other information into seat predictions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The table below lists some of the predictions.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Some predictions cover Northern Ireland, with its distinct political culture, while others do not.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Parties are sorted by current number of seats in the House of Commons.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An exit poll, collected by Ipsos MORI and GfK on behalf of the BBC, ITN and Sky News, was published at 10 pm at the end of voting.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This predicted the Conservatives to be 10 seats short of an absolute majority, although with the 5 predicted Sinn Féin MPs not taking their seats, it was likely to be enough to govern – although Sinn Féin eventually only won 4 seats.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The exit poll was markedly different from pre-election polls, which had been fairly consistent; this led many pundits and MPs to speculate that the exit poll was inaccurate, and that the final result would have the two main parties closer to each other.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown vowed to "eat his hat" and former Labour "spin doctor" Alastair Campbell promised to "eat his kilt" if the exit poll was right.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] As it turned out, the results were even more favourable to the Conservatives than the poll predicted, with the Conservatives obtaining 330 seats, an absolute majority.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ashdown and Campbell were presented with hat- and kilt-shaped cakes (labelled "eat me") on BBC *Question Time* on 8 May.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] With the eventual outcome in terms of both votes and seats varying substantially from the bulk of opinion polls released in the final months before the election, the polling industry received criticism for their inability to predict what was a surprisingly clear Conservative victory.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Several theories were put forward to explain the inaccuracy of the pollsters: one was that there had simply been a very late swing to the Conservatives, with Survation claiming that 13% of voters made up their minds in the final days and 17% on the day of the election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Survation also claimed that a poll they carried out a day before the election gave the Conservatives 37% and Labour 31%, though they said they did not release the poll (commissioned by the *Daily Mirror*) on the concern that it was too much of an outlier with other poll results.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] However, it was reported that pollsters had in fact picked up a very late swing to Labour immediately prior to polling day, not the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It was reported after the election that private pollsters working for the two largest parties actually gathered more accurate results, with Labour's pollster James Morris claiming that the issue was largely to do with surveying technique.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Another theory was that 'shy Tories' did not want to openly declare their intention to vote Conservative to pollsters – this was the case in 1992, the last time pollsters significantly missed.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A final theory was the 'Lazy Labour' factor, which claimed that Labour voters tend to not vote on polling day whereas Conservative voters have a much higher turnout.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The British Polling Council announced an inquiry into the substantial variance between the opinion polls and the actual election result.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The inquiry published preliminary findings in January 2016, concluding that "the ways in which polling samples are constructed was the primary cause of the polling miss".
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Their final report was published in March 2016.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The British Election Study team suggested that weighting error appeared to be the cause.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The following table shows final election results as reported by BBC News and *The Guardian*.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] 66 parties are grouped together as 'other parties'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This column shows the change in vote share percentage from the 2010 general election to the 2015 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] BBC News includes the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, in the MP tally and the vote tally for the Conservatives.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] See About these results, BBC News (30 April 2015).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In this table, however, the speaker (who usually does not vote in the Commons) is listed separately, and has been removed from the Conservative tally.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The UUP did not run itself in 2010; instead, it ran candidates under the Ulster Conservatives and Unionists banner.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] BBC News lists the National Health Action Party together with Independent Community and Health Concern (formerly known as Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern), which is affiliated with the larger party, for a total of 20,210 votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] *The Guardian* lists each party separately.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Health Concern received 7,211 of the votes attributed to the National Health Action Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The BBC groups together the votes under the Scottish Christian Party (1,467 votes); Christian Party (1,040 votes); and Christian (698 votes) labels, for a total of 3,205 votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] *The Guardian* lists these designations separately.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Guardian lists the vote totals for the Communist Party of Britain, Communist Party, Scottish Communist Party Conservatives, and the designation "Communist" separately.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In this table, these designations are grouped into a single Communist tally.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] One result of the 2015 general election was that a different political party won the popular vote in each of the countries of the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This was reflected in terms of MPs elected: The Conservatives won in England with 319 MPs out of 533 constituencies, the SNP won in Scotland with 56 out of 59, Labour won in Wales with 25 out of 40, and the Democratic Unionist Party won in Northern Ireland with 8 out of 18.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Thus the result bore resemblance to 1992.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Conservatives gained 38 seats while losing 10, all to Labour; Employment Minister Esther McVey, in Wirral West, was the most senior Conservative to lose her seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Labour Party polled below expectations, winning 30.4% of the vote and 232 seats, 24 fewer than its previous result in 2010—even though in 222 constituencies there was a Conservative-to-Labour swing, as against 151 constituencies where there was a Labour-to-Conservative swing.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Its net loss of seats were mainly a result of its resounding defeat in Scotland, where the Scottish National Party took 40 of Labour's 41 seats, unseating key politicians such as shadow Foreign Secretary Douglas Alexander and Scottish Labour leader Jim Murphy.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour gained some seats in London and other major cities, but lost a further nine seats to the Conservatives, recording its lowest share of the seats since the 1987 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ed Miliband subsequently tendered his resignation as Labour leader.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Scottish National Party had a stunning election, rising from just 6 seats to 56 – winning all but 3 of the constituencies in Scotland and securing 50% of the popular vote in Scotland.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] They recorded a number of record breaking swings of over 30% including the new record of 39.3% in Glasgow North East.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] They also won the seat of former Prime Minister Gordon Brown, overturning a majority of 23,009 to win by a majority of 9,974 votes and saw Mhairi Black, then a 20-year-old student, defeat Labour's Shadow Foreign Secretary Douglas Alexander with a swing of 26.9%.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Liberal Democrats, who had been in government as coalition partners, suffered the worst defeat they or the previous Liberal Party had suffered since the 1970 general election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Winning just eight seats, the Liberal Democrats lost their position as the UK's third party and found themselves tied in fourth place with the Democratic Unionist Party of Northern Ireland in the House of Commons, with Nick Clegg being one of the few MPs from his party to retain his seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Liberal Democrats gained no seats, while losing 49 in the process—of them, 27 to the Conservatives, 12 to Labour, and 10 to the SNP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The party also lost their deposit in 341 seats, the same number as in every general election from 1979 to 2010 combined.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The party lost all of their seats in the South West Region, a typical stronghold.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It was the first time since 1966 (as the Liberal Party) that they won 0 seats in the Region.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The UK Independence Party (UKIP) held only one of its two seats, Clacton, gaining no new ones despite increasing its vote share to 12.9% (the third-highest share overall).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Party leader Nigel Farage, having failed to win the constituency of South Thanet, tendered his resignation, although this was rejected by his party's executive council and he stayed on as leader.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionist Party returned to the Commons with two MPs after a five-year absence, gaining one seat from the Democratic Unionist Party and one from Sinn Féin, while the Alliance Party lost its only Commons seat to the DUP, despite an increase in total vote share.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The election led to an increase in the number of female MPs, to 191 (29% of the total, including 99 Labour; 68 Conservative; 20 SNP; 4 other) from 147 (23% of the total, including 87 Labour; 47 Conservative; 7 Liberal Democrat; 1 SNP; 5 other).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] As before the election, the region with the largest proportion of women MPs was North East England.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] 111 seats changed hands compared to the result in 2010 plus three by-election gains reverted to the party that won the seat at the last general election in 2010 (Bradford West, Corby and Rochester and Strood).
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 8 May, three party leaders announced their resignations within an hour of each other: Ed Miliband (Labour) and Nick Clegg (Liberal Democrat) resigned due to their parties' worse-than-expected results in the election, although both had been re-elected to their seats in Parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Nigel Farage (UKIP) offered his resignation because he had failed to be elected as MP for South Thanet, but said he might re-stand in the resulting leadership election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] However, on 11 May, the UKIP executive rejected his resignation on the grounds that the election campaign had been "a great success", and Farage agreed to continue as party leader.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Alan Sugar, a Labour peer in the House of Lords, also announced his resignation from the Labour Party for running what he perceived to be an anti-business campaign.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In response to Labour's poor performance in Scotland, Scottish Labour leader Jim Murphy initially resisted calls for his resignation by other senior party members.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Despite surviving a no-confidence vote by 17–14 from the party's national executive, Murphy announced he would step down as leader on or before 16 May.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Financial markets reacted positively to the result, with the pound sterling rising against the Euro and US dollar when the exit poll was published, and the FTSE 100 stock market index rising 2.3% on 8 May.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The BBC reported: "Bank shares saw some of the biggest gains, on hopes that the sector will not see any further rises in levies.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Shares in Lloyds Banking Group rose 5.75% while Barclays was 3.7% higher", adding: "Energy firms also saw their share prices rise, as Labour had wanted a price freeze and more powers for the energy regulator.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] British Gas owner Centrica rose 8.1% and SSE shares were up 5.3%." BBC economics editor Robert Peston noted: "To state the obvious, investors love the Tories' general election victory.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] One (no surprise here) is that Labour's threat of breaking up banks and imposing energy price caps has been lifted.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Second is that investors have been discounting days and weeks of wrangling after polling day over who would form the government – and so they are semi-euphoric that we already know who's in charge.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The disparity between the numbers of votes and the number of seats obtained by the smaller parties gave rise to increased calls for replacement of the 'first-past-the-post' voting system with a more proportional system.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] For example, UKIP had 3.9 million votes per seat, whereas SNP had just 26,000 votes per seat, about 150 times greater representation for each vote cast.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UKIP stood in 10 times as many seats as the SNP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The ICO concluded that subscribers had not expressed their consent to receive this kind of direct marketing.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Four electors from Orkney and Shetland lodged an election petition on 29 May 2015 attempting to unseat Alistair Carmichael and force a by-election over what became known as 'Frenchgate'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The veracity of the memo was quickly denied by the French ambassador, French consul general and Sturgeon.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 9 December, an Election Court decided that although he had told a "blatant lie" in a TV interview, it had not been proven beyond reasonable doubt that he had committed an "illegal practice" under the Representation of the People Act and he was allowed to retain his seat.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The higher fine for the Conservatives reflected both the extent of the wrongdoing (which extended to the 2014 parliamentary by-elections in Clacton, Newark and Rochester and Strood) and 'the unreasonable uncooperative conduct by the Party'.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The commission also found that the Party Treasurer, Simon Day, may not have fulfilled his obligations under the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000 and referred him for investigation to the Metropolitan Police Service.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] At constituency level, related alleged breaches of spending regulations led to 'unprecedented' police investigations for possible criminal conduct of between 20 and 30 Conservative Party MPs.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 9 May 2017, the Crown Prosecution Service decided not to prosecute the vast majority of suspects, saying that "in order to bring a charge, it must be proved that a suspect knew the return was inaccurate and acted dishonestly in signing the declaration.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Appearing at Westminster Magistrates' Court on 4 July 2017, the three pleased not guilty and were released on unconditional bail pending an appearance at Southwark Crown Court on 1 August 2017.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The investigation of Party Treasurer Simon Day remained ongoing.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In 2016–18, the European Parliament found that UKIP had unlawfully spent over €173,000 of EU funding on the party's 2015 UK election campaign, via the Alliance for Direct Democracy in Europe and the affiliated Institute for Direct Democracy.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Parliament required the repayment of the mis-spent funds and denied the organisations some other funding.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It also found that UKIP MEPs had unlawfully spent EU money on other assistance for national campaigning purposes during 2014–16 and docked their salaries to recoup the mis-spent funds.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The **2016 London Assembly election** was an election held on 5 May 2016 to elect the members of the London Assembly.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] It took place on the same day as the London mayoral election and the United Kingdom local elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] Four parties had AMs in the previous Assembly: London Labour led by Len Duvall, London Conservatives led by Gareth Bacon, London Greens led by Siân Berry, and the London Liberal Democrats led by Caroline Pidgeon.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] Labour received the largest number of votes ever cast for a party in a London Assembly election, becoming the first party to poll over 1 million votes.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] Although they gained Merton and Wandsworth from the Conservatives, their regional vote share declined by 0.8%, and they finished with 12 AMs, the same as in 2012.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The Conservative Party won just 8 Assembly seats, its worst-ever performance in a London Assembly election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The Green Party retained its 2 Assembly members, although its 8.0% share of the regional vote represented its worst-ever result, and UKIP returned to the London Assembly for the first time since the election of 2004.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The Liberal Democrats elected just 1 AM, their worst-ever result.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] Of the minor parties, the newly formed Women's Equality Party was the most successful, attracting 91,772 votes (3.51%) on the regional list, which did not entitle them to any Assembly members as the threshold for representation is 5% of the regional vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The election system used is called the Additional Member System.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] There are 14 constituencies that elect one member each to the Assembly.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] These seats have been won only by the Labour Party or the Conservative Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The remaining 11 seats are distributed by a second vote, by a modified D'Hondt method of closed-list voting, with a 5% minimum threshold.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] These seats have been won by other parties too, namely the Green Party, the Liberal Democrats and UKIP, and in the past the British National Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] The overall result is an attempted compromise between constituency representation and London-wide proportional representation.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] Those who were eligible had to be registered to vote before 19 April 2016 in order to take part in this election.
[src:animal-welfare-party/2016-london-assembly-election] Note that party descriptions can be used as alternatives to the registered party name.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] The party was founded in December 2006 by Jasmijn de Boo, a Dutch national, of Kennington, London, and Shaun Rutherford of Milford Haven, Wales, as Animals Count!
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] The party was registered with the Electoral Commission on 22 January 2007.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In October 2010, Vanessa Hudson was elected as party leader.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In 2013, the party changed its name from Animals Count! to the Animal Welfare Party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In June 2013, Hudson joined leaders from other animal protection parties from across Europe in a meeting in The Hague organised by the Animal Politics Foundation of the Netherlands.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] At this meeting the animal protection parties of the Netherlands, Spain, Portugal, Germany, Denmark, Italy, Turkey and the UK discussed ways in which they could work together more effectively.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] Later that month, Hudson announced that the Animal Welfare Party would stand in the London region in the 2014 European Parliament elections.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] It was one of seven European animal protection parties contesting the 2014 European elections with the aim of returning dedicated representatives for animals to the EU Parliament.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] This European group of parties became known informally as the EuroAnimal7 and included PvdD of The Netherlands, PACMA of Spain, PAN of Portugal, Partei Mensch Umwelt Tierschutz of Germany, Djurens Parti of Sweden, and Animal Party Cyprus.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In September 2017, the party gained its first elected representative after Alsager Town Councillor Jane Smith defected from the Green Party to the AWP.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In January 2024, the party gained a second representative after Hexham Town Councillor Lee Williscroft-Ferris, who had been elected as an independent, switched to the party.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] The party's main goal is "a world in which animals are not exploited and are seen and treated as sentient beings".
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] It describes itself as "primarily dedicated to advancing the rights of all non-human animals" and as "modelled on the successful Dutch Party for the Animals".
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] It also postulates left-wing economic policies outside of animal issues; it advocates a 50% tax rate for those earning more than £150,000, in 2018 supported an increase of the minimum wage to £10 per hour, and supports reducing the private sector in housing in favour of the public sector.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] It initially intended to stand in the Welsh Assembly election in 2007.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In the 2008 London Assembly election, de Boo stood in Lambeth and Southwark, receiving 1,828 votes (1.12%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] The party sponsored an electoral list of three candidates for the 2009 European Parliament election in the East of England, receiving 13,201 votes (0.8%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] In the 2010 United Kingdom general election, the party contested one seat, which it did not win.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] The party sponsored an electoral list of eight candidates for the 2014 European Parliament election in the London region, receiving 21,092 votes (1.0%).
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] Four AWP candidates contested the 2015 general election, all losing their deposits.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] They stood in the 2016 London Assembly election, receiving 1% of the vote.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] They stood four candidates in the 2017 general election and six in the 2019 general election: none were elected.
[src:animal-welfare-party/animal-welfare-party] They stood again in the 2021 and 2024 London Assembly elections, receiving 1.7% of the vote both times.
